# CMake + Project Structure + Menuconfig

---

## 1. What Is a Build System?

When you write code in a file — say `main.c` — the computer cannot run it directly. It needs to be compiled into machine code first. On a small project with one file, you could compile manually:

```bash
gcc main.c -o my_program
```

But in a real project you have dozens or hundreds of files. You have libraries. You have different settings for debug vs release builds. You have multiple chips to target. Doing this manually is impossible.

A **build system** is a tool that knows:

- Which files need to be compiled
- In what order to compile them
- Which libraries to link
- What flags to use
- When to recompile (only changed files — not everything)

### PC Analogy

Think of building a house. You have:

- Architects who draw the plans (your source code)
- A **project manager** who reads the plans and tells each worker what to do in what order (the build system — CMake)
- Workers who do the actual construction (the compiler — GCC/Clang)
- Tools the workers use (hammer, drill — compiler flags)

CMake is the project manager. You write the plans. CMake figures out the rest.

### Build System Comparison

|Tool|Used by|What it does|
|---|---|---|
|Arduino IDE|Arduino|Hides everything — one button compile|
|Make|Old C projects|Simple but hard to scale|
|CMake|ESP-IDF, Qt, Linux|Modern, cross-platform, scalable|
|Gradle|Android|Java/Kotlin projects|
|npm/webpack|Web|JavaScript projects|

ESP-IDF uses CMake. Once you understand it — you understand how most professional C/C++ projects are built.

