## 3. CMakeLists.txt — The Two Files

Every ESP-IDF project has **two** CMakeLists.txt files. This confuses beginners. Here is exactly what each one does.

### File 1 — Root CMakeLists.txt

This is the top-level project definition. It tells CMake:

- What this project is called
- Where to find ESP-IDF
- What the minimum CMake version is

```cmake
cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.16)

include($ENV{IDF_PATH}/tools/cmake/project.cmake)

project(my_project)
```

That is it. Three lines. You almost never change this file.

|Line|What it does|
|---|---|
|`cmake_minimum_required`|CMake version check — ensures compatibility|
|`include(...)`|Loads all ESP-IDF build rules and toolchain|
|`project(my_project)`|Names your project — appears in build output|

### File 2 — main/CMakeLists.txt

This is the component-level definition. It tells CMake:

- Which source files belong to this component
- Which other components this component needs

```cmake
idf_component_register(
    SRCS "main.c"
    INCLUDE_DIRS "."
)
```

|Line|What it does|
|---|---|
|`idf_component_register`|Registers this folder as an ESP-IDF component|
|`SRCS "main.c"`|List of source files to compile|
|`INCLUDE_DIRS "."`|Folders where header files are found|

### Adding More Source Files

```cmake
idf_component_register(
    SRCS
        "main.c"
        "wifi_manager.c"
        "sensor_reader.c"
    INCLUDE_DIRS "."
    REQUIRES
        nvs_flash
        esp_wifi
        driver
)
```

`REQUIRES` lists which ESP-IDF components your code depends on. CMake uses this to pull in the right libraries automatically.

