## 5. What idf.py set-target Does

This is one of the most important commands — and most misunderstood.

```bash
idf.py set-target esp32
idf.py set-target esp32s3
idf.py set-target esp32c3
```

When you run this, ESP-IDF:

1. Sets the correct compiler toolchain (Xtensa GCC for ESP32/S3, RISC-V GCC for C3/C6)
2. Sets the correct memory layout for that chip
3. Sets the correct peripheral register addresses
4. Generates a base sdkconfig for that chip
5. Clears any previous build output

### Why This Matters

```
ESP32     uses Xtensa LX6   -> xtensa-esp32-elf-gcc compiler
ESP32-S3  uses Xtensa LX7   -> xtensa-esp32s3-elf-gcc compiler
ESP32-C3  uses RISC-V       -> riscv32-esp-elf-gcc compiler
```

The same C code — different binary output for each chip. `set-target` switches which compiler and which chip config to use.

**Rule:** Run `idf.py set-target` once when creating a project. If you change the target — run `idf.py fullclean` first to wipe the old build.

