## 7. sdkconfig — What Gets Generated

After you run menuconfig and save, ESP-IDF generates a file called `sdkconfig`.

```
# Automatically generated file — DO NOT EDIT
CONFIG_IDF_TARGET="esp32"
CONFIG_FREERTOS_HZ=1000
CONFIG_ESP_DEFAULT_CPU_FREQ_MHZ_240=y
CONFIG_ESP_WIFI_STATIC_RX_BUFFER_NUM=10
CONFIG_LOG_DEFAULT_LEVEL_INFO=y
CONFIG_LOG_DEFAULT_LEVEL=3
...
(hundreds more lines)
```

### The Golden Rule

**Never manually edit sdkconfig.**

It is auto-generated. Any manual changes get overwritten next time you run menuconfig. If you need to set a default value — use `sdkconfig.defaults`.

### sdkconfig.defaults

This is the file you control. Put only the settings you want to override:

```
# sdkconfig.defaults
CONFIG_FREERTOS_HZ=1000
CONFIG_ESP_DEFAULT_CPU_FREQ_MHZ=240
CONFIG_LOG_DEFAULT_LEVEL_WARN=y
CONFIG_ESP_WIFI_STATIC_RX_BUFFER_NUM=16
```

ESP-IDF applies these defaults every time someone runs `idf.py menuconfig` on a fresh clone of your repo. This is how you share consistent config across a team.

### PC Analogy

|File|PC Equivalent|
|---|---|
|`sdkconfig`|Windows Registry — auto-generated, system managed|
|`sdkconfig.defaults`|Group Policy — your organisation's baseline settings|

