## 8. Components — Splitting Your Code

As your project grows, putting everything in `main.c` becomes unmanageable. ESP-IDF solves this with **components** — self-contained code modules.

### What a Component Is

A component is a folder with:

- Its own `CMakeLists.txt`
- One or more `.c` source files
- One or more `.h` header files

```
components/
+-- wifi_manager/
|   +-- CMakeLists.txt
|   +-- wifi_manager.h      <- Public API — what others can use
|   +-- wifi_manager.c      <- Implementation — private details
|
+-- sensor_reader/
    +-- CMakeLists.txt
    +-- sensor_reader.h
    +-- sensor_reader.c
```

### Component CMakeLists.txt

```cmake
idf_component_register(
    SRCS "wifi_manager.c"
    INCLUDE_DIRS "."
    REQUIRES
        esp_wifi
        nvs_flash
        esp_event
)
```

### Using a Component in main.c

```c
#include "wifi_manager.h"      // Include the component header
#include "sensor_reader.h"

void app_main(void) {
    wifi_manager_init();
    wifi_manager_connect("MySSID", "MyPassword");

    sensor_reader_init();
    float temp = sensor_reader_get_temperature();
}
```

### main/CMakeLists.txt — Declaring the Dependency

```cmake
idf_component_register(
    SRCS "main.c"
    INCLUDE_DIRS "."
    REQUIRES
        wifi_manager       <- Your custom component
        sensor_reader      <- Your custom component
)
```

### PC Analogy

|Concept|PC Equivalent|
|---|---|
|Component|A DLL / shared library|
|`wifi_manager.h`|The DLL's public API header|
|`wifi_manager.c`|The DLL's internal implementation|
|`REQUIRES` in CMakeLists|Import / linker dependency declaration|

